    "jtbd": {
      "when": "You want the job the customer 'hires' the product to do.",
      "why": "Reframing features as outcomes uncovers white space — a snack brand grew by serving the 'afternoon slump' job, not 'taste'.",
      "how": "JTBD outputs feed directly into product roadmap (build for the job, not the feature), messaging (speak to the outcome, not the tool), and competitive positioning (you're not competing with similar products — you're competing with the old way of getting the job done).",
      "example": "When a team asks 'what feature should we build next?', JTBD reframes the question as 'what job is the customer hiring this product for?' — shifting from feature lists to outcome-driven roadmaps.",
      "tags": [
        "jobs",
        "customer",
        "innovation",
        "switch interview",
        "push pull",
        "motivation",
        "outcome",
        "why they switch",
        "hiring",
        "functional emotional social"
      ],
      "sections": [
        "Product"
      ],
      "compare": "vs Value Prop: focus on the JOB hired, not the offer · vs Persona Deep Dive: persona = who, JTBD = what they hire the product to do in context",
      "skill": [
        {
          "title": "Your Job Statement",
          "body": "Fill in: 'When [your customer's specific circumstance], I want to [the progress they seek], so I can [the outcome they value].' Rules: Never mention your product name. Include the situation, not demographics. Name functional AND emotional progress. Example pattern: 'When I'm [situation], I want to [progress], so I can [outcome].' Bad: 'I want your app.' Good: 'When I'm overwhelmed and don't know where to start, I want to see my priorities clearly so I can feel in control.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Your Four Forces",
          "body": "For YOUR proposed change, fill in: PUSH — What frustrates your customer about the current way? PULL — What attracts them to your solution? ANXIETY — What fears block the switch? HABIT — What keeps them doing it the old way? Change only happens when Push + Pull > Habit + Anxiety. Most teams only increase Pull. What specific intervention will YOU design for Anxiety? For Habit?"
        },
        {
          "title": "Your Competitive Landscape",
          "body": "For YOUR customer's job, list: OBVIOUS competitor (same category as you): ___ NON-OBVIOUS competitors (different category, same job): ___ NON-CONSUMPTION (doing nothing — the most common competitor): ___ Positioning answer: 'We are the best hire for [job], not the best [category].' What job are YOU the best hire for?"
        },
        {
          "title": "Your Big Hire vs Little Hire",
          "body": "BIG HIRE (purchase): What metric tracks first-time conversion? ___ What reduces purchase anxiety? ___ LITTLE HIRE (usage): What metric tracks repeat usage? ___ What drives the return? ___ Diagnosis: High Big Hire + Low Little Hire = won the pitch, lost the experience. Low Big Hire + High Little Hire = great product, bad marketing. Which diagnosis fits YOUR situation?"
        },
        {
          "title": "Your Three Dimensions",
          "body": "For YOUR job statement, verify: FUNCTIONAL — What tangible progress does your customer need? ___ EMOTIONAL — How do they want to feel? (control, safety, accomplishment) ___ SOCIAL — How do they want to be perceived? (professional, responsible, smart) ___ Most teams nail Functional, forget Emotional, ignore Social. Which dimension are YOU missing?"
        },
        {
          "title": "Your JTBD Maturity Score",
          "body": "Score 1 point for each YES: (1) Can you state the job without mentioning your product? (2) Have you mapped all four forces? (3) Do you know the emotional and social dimensions? (4) Have you identified non-obvious competitors? (5) Are you tracking Little Hire separately? (6) Can your team explain how each feature serves the job? (7) Have you interviewed customers about their purchase timeline? YOUR SCORE: ___/7. Lowest-scoring item = fix next."
        }
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "title": "Job Statement Pattern",
          "body": "Bad: 'I want a to-do app' (mentions product). Good: 'When I'm overwhelmed with tasks, I want to see my priorities clearly so I can feel in control of my day.' Your turn: write yours using 'When [circumstance], I want [progress], so I can [outcome].'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Non-Obvious Competition Pattern",
          "body": "Your obvious competitor = same category. Non-obvious = different category, same job. Non-consumption = doing nothing. Example: 'Commute entertainment' — obvious: other podcasts. Non-obvious: music, phone calls. Non-consumption: boredom. Your turn: list yours."
        },
        {
          "title": "Big Hire vs Little Hire Pattern",
          "body": "Big Hire = first purchase. Little Hire = repeat usage. If customers buy but don't use, you won Big Hire, lost Little Hire. Track them separately. Your turn: what's YOUR Big Hire metric? YOUR Little Hire metric?"
        }
      ],
      "casestudy": [
        {
          "title": "Pebble Watch — Won functional, lost social",
          "body": "Functional job clear. Social dimension missed — mainstream users felt self-conscious. Apple Watch solved social (fashion, luxury). Your question: which dimension are YOU ignoring?",
          "result": "failure"
        },
        {
          "title": "Intercom — Every feature names its job",
          "body": "Feature proposal must name the job it serves. 'Better reporting' became 'prove to my boss support is working' → automated emails, not dashboards. Your question: can YOUR team name the job for each feature?",
          "result": "success"
        }
      ],
      "integration": [
        {
          "title": "JTBD × Mom Test",
          "body": "JTBD = WHAT/WHY of the job. Mom Test = HOW to ask without leading. Use Mom Test techniques during JTBD interviews — ask about past behavior, not hypotheticals."
        },
        {
          "title": "JTBD × Four Steps",
          "body": "JTBD tells you WHAT to build. Four Steps tells you HOW to validate it. JTBD interviews = Customer Discovery. Job Statement = your hypothesis."
        },
        {
          "title": "JTBD × Value Proposition Canvas",
          "body": "JTBD provides the INPUT (job, forces, dimensions). VPC provides the STRUCTURE (gains, pains, gain creators, pain relievers). Map your job to VPC elements."
        }
      ]
    },
